{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505914"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:37:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:37:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2497"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2497"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.06,0.13,0.1,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109530"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2497"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42510"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109530"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to a new General Practitioner with a facial rash which has spread to her arms over the last three weeks. She reports having several episodes of sunburn to her face several months ago which spontaneously resolved but have left behind a scar. She has also been feeling generally unwell with subjective fevers. She describes her fingertips turning purple in cooler weather. Other things she has noticed include thinning of her hair and joint pains that she thinks is from all the heavy lifting at work. She is otherwise healthy without any significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a current smoker of 10 cigarettes per day. She reports her mother has thyroid disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient reports when she had a similar episode several months ago, blood tests were done by another GP. She cannot remember what their clinical suspicion was at the time and was lost to follow up. She does report she was encouraged to stop smoking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn review of those blood tests, the ANA titre was 1:2560. Full blood count and biochemistry were unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following dermatological signs of this condition include is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acrokeratosis verruciformis of Hopf","Positive Nikolsky sign","Gottron papules","Poikiloderma","Discoid rash"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E (SLE).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscoid rash\u003C/strong\u003E presents usually as round, coin-shaped lesions most commonly in the face. They are photosensitive and typically lead to keratotic scales and atrophic scarring. The systemic features suggest SLE, rather than cutaneous lupus erythematosus. The typical patient demographic of systemic lupus erythematosus is a woman of childbearing age. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003ECutaneous features of SLE can include: \u003Cbr /\u003E- Acute: Butterfly rash, bullous systemic lupus erythematosus, maculopapular rash, mucosal erosions and ulcerations, photosensitivity, nonscarring alopecia \u003Cbr /\u003E- Subacute: psoriasiform rash or annular polycyclic rash \u003Cbr /\u003E- Chronic: indurated hyperpigmented plaques in discoid lupus, hypertrophic (warty) lupus \u003Cbr /\u003ENonspecific cutaneous SLE features can include: nail fold capillary telangiectasia, Raynaud phenomenon, vasculopathy of digit tips, diffuse hair thinning, urticaria, livedo reticularis, and calcinosis cutis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA positive Nikolsky sign occurs in Stevens-Johnson syndrome, toxic epidermal necrolysis, staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome, and can occur in pemphigus vulgaris.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGottron papules are a pathognomonic sign of dermatomyositis. Poikiloderma is also characteristic of dermatomyositis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcrokeratosis verruciformis of Hopf is typical of Darier\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe 2019 EULAR/ACR criteria is the most recent diagnostic criteria developed for SLE.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A butterfly rash is typical of lupus erythematosus."],"references":["Aringer M, Costenbader K, Daikh D, et al. 2019 European League Against Rheumatism/American College of Rheumatology classification criteria for systemic lupus erythematosus. Arthritis Rheumatol 2019; 71(9):1400-1412.","Fortuna G, Brennan MT. Systemic lupus erythematosus: epidemiology, pathophysiology, manifestations, and management. Dent Clin North Am. 2013 Oct;57(4):631-55. doi: 10.1016/j.cden.2013.06.003. PMID: 24034070."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2497"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1664"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1664"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jp